ns are a growing group in most Roman Catholic congregations.In their introduction, Timothy Matovina and Gary Riebe-Estrella analyze the ways Mexican rituals and beliefs pose significant challenges and opportunities for Catholicism in the United States. Original essays by theologians, historians, and ethnographers provide a rich interdisciplinary dialogue on how religious traditions function for Mexican American Catholics, revealing the symbolic world at the heart of their spirituality. The authors speak to the diverse meanings behind these ceremonies, explaining that Mexican American (and other Latino) Catholics use them to express not only religious devotion, but also ethnic identity and patriotism, solidarity, and, in some cases, their condition as exiles. The result is a multilayered vision of Mexican American religion, which touches as well on issues of racism and discrimination, poverty, and the role of women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMexican American CatholicsxHistory. 4aReligious Studies. 4aU.S. History. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh1 aCadena, Gilbert R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEspin, Orlando O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoizueta, Roberto S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeon, Luis D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMary Davalos, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatovina, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatovina, Timothy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMedina, Lara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRiebe-Estrella, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary